where weekly church services were held with a small number of people. Members also established  stake centers where larger groups of members could congregate and worship, though less frequently. The design of these church buildings varied based on the religious purpose. The more religiously esteemed or valued a church building was, the more funding and attention to the architectural design it received.   \n\n=== 1847-1860 ===\nWhen the church was first organized, people normally met in  one room of a house or the upstairs of a building. However, once the church had gathered in Utah, one room buildings were built and used as meeting houses, but also served other, often secular purposes. As years went, on more established designs including columns and steeples began to be included in the development of meetinghouses. The use of columns and steeples was a style that was known as \"eclectic or of vernacular 'high style.'\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/digital/collection/EoM/id/3913|title=Meetinghouse|website=contentdm.lib.byu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> This style was a simple, yet effective architectural style in providing religious enlightenment with the steeple symbolizing the connection between heaven and earth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://werdsmith.com/p/0R2AbZFhY|title=History of the Church Steeple|last=Taylor|first=Justin|date=|website=werdsmith.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n=== 1860-1890 ===\nAs the church grew and more financially acquit in Utah, more meetinghouses were built with features recognized by members today. Joseph Don Carlos Young, the son of Brigham Young, was a prominent architect during this time. One of his most significant accomplishments in his architectural career was his creation of the [[Brigham Young University|Brigham Young Academy]] in 1890.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://utahcfa.org/architect/joseph_don_-carlos_young|title=UCFA \u00bb Architect \u00bb Joseph Don Carlos Young|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n== Pioneer Homes ==\n[[File:Pioneer Home built for Jacob Hamblin in 1862.jpg|thumb|Jacob Hamblin home built in 1862, Santa Clara, Utah]]\n\n=== Polygamous Homes ===\n[[Mormonism and polygamy|Polygamy]] was practiced during the early days of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints. In many situations, plural wives would live together in one home rather than spread out individually. Consequently, homes would be built in a way that had designated quarters or divisions to give each wife a private section. Living situations among the wives were determined based on income, number of wives, and how well the wives got along.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bennion|first=Lowell C.|url=https://lib.byu.edu|title=Polygamy in Lorenzo Snow's Brigham City: An Architectural Tour|publisher=Western Regional Architecture Program, College of Architecture and Planning, University of Utah|year=2005|isbn=|location=Salt Lake City, UT|pages=}}</ref> \n\n== Theatres, Schools, and other Institutions ==\nThe Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints emphasized and valued entertainment in ways such as theatre and music. Eventually, the Salt Lake Theatre was established and stood as an excellent theatre to all who visited. In addition the theatres, education was a value that many English-born and northern American members brought with them to Utah. This resulting in the establishment of many schools. The Mormon Tabernacle Choir eventually evolved from the Nauvoo Choir and was established in the 1850's.<ref name=\":2\" />  \n\n=== Theatres ===\n[[File:Brigham Young's Theatre, Salt Lake City. (18595826252).jpg|thumb|Brigham Young's Theatre, Salt Lake City, 1868-1870]]\nAfter the Saints arrived in the Salt Lake Valley and established themselves, a need for entertainment emerged. While traveling across the plains, the Saint's source of entertainment came from singing and dancing around the campfire when they had the energy. The first performances were performed in places of worship, one in particular being the Bowery.<ref>Monsos, Mike. [https://lib.byu.edu A Brief History of Theatres in Utah]. vol. 42, 2006.</ref> Associations such as The Desert Drama Association were created. The first actual theatre was the Social Hall, then the Bowrings Theatre, and then the Salt Lake Theatre. These were all built before 1862. The Salt Lake Theatre was one of the most popular attractions for sixty years. It was only until after World War I when the film industry increased that the Theatre lost popularity and was eventually demolished in 1928.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pioneertheatre.org/about-us/history/the-salt-lake-theatre/|title=The Salt Lake Theatre|website=Pioneer Theatre Company|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> The buildings focused on replicating opera houses resulting in very elegant architecture. While these buildings did not contain the same sacredness as the temples, they still received the same dedication, focus, and craftsmanship in their construction.  \n\n=== Schools ===\nThe first schools were often held in the one room meetinghouse the Saints also used for church services. <ref name=\":0\" /> [[Education in Utah]] was one that consisted of Mormon schools, anti-Mormon schools, and religious schools of other denominations. \n\n=== The Tabernacle ===\n[[File:Mormon Tabernacle 1870s.jpg|thumb|Mormon Tabernacle in the 1870s]]\nIn order for the members to have large gatherings where they could hear both the choir and the church leaders, buildings such as the Tabernacle were built. Architecturally, the Tabernacle served as a middle ground between the extravagance of the temples and the plainness of the meetinghouses. This building was built under the direction of President Brigham Young. The tabernacle has a unique style which consists of an expansive dome cover, allowing sound to reverberate well throughout the building. It is a two story building with a main floor and a balcony.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jackson, Richard W.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/54394707|title=Places of worship : 150 years of Latter-day Saint architecture|date=2003|publisher=Religious Studies Center, Brigham Young University|isbn=1-59156-390-9|oclc=54394707}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hansen|first=Brett|title=Gathering Strength|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1061/ciegag.0000134|journal=Civil Engineering Magazine Archive|volume=77|issue=8|pages=46\u201353|doi=10.1061/ciegag.0000134|issn=2381-0688|via=}}</ref> Saints gathered here for [[General Conference (LDS Church)|general conference]] until 2000 when the Conference Center was built.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/church/news/a-brief-history-of-general-conference?lang=eng|title=A Brief History of General Conference|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  \n\n== References ==\n{{dashboard.wikiedu.org sandbox}}\n", "name_user": "Djgonzophd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Pioneer_Style_in_Utah"}
{"title_page": "Katie McGrath", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish actress}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Katie McGrath\n| caption            = McGrath at Comic Con France in 2010\n| birth_date         = <!-- Per WP:DOB, do NOT add unless a strong source (i.e. an article) is provided. Unsourced comments from her co-stars DO NOT count. -->\n| birth_place        = [[Ashford, County Wicklow]], Ireland\n| education          = Trinity College, Dublin<ref name=\"TheGloss1\" />\n| occupation         = Actress <!-- DO NOT add model here as McGrath is not known for being a model -->\n| yearsactive        = 2007\u2013present\n| spouse             = caitlin :)\n}}\n\n'''Katie McGrath''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|'|g|r|\u0251:}})<!--Do NOT add her birthday unless a strong source (i.e. an article) is provided. Unsourced comments from her co-stars DO NOT count. --> is an Irish actress.<!-- NOTE: She is primarily known as an actress. \"Model\" is in the infobox.--><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/what-katies-doing-next-k38hrgn77vh|title=What Katie\u2019s doing next|last=|first=|date=|work=thetimes.co.uk|access-date=1 October 2019|language=en}}</ref> In television, she is best known for portraying [[Morgan le Fay|Morgana]] on the [[BBC One]] series [[Merlin (2008 TV series)|''Merlin'']] (2008\u20132012), [[Lucy Westenra]] on the British-American series ''[[Dracula (2013 TV series)|Dracula]]'' (2013\u20132014), Sarah Bennett in the first season of the Canadian horror anthology series ''[[Slasher (TV series)|Slasher]]'' (2016) and for her role as [[Lena Luthor]] on the American superhero series ''[[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]]'' (2016\u2013present). Her film roles include [[Thelma Furness, Viscountess Furness|Lady Thelma Furness]] in the drama film ''[[W.E.]]'' and Jules Daley in the Christmas movie  ''[[A Princess for Christmas]]'', (2011), Zara Young in the science fiction adventure film ''[[Jurassic World]]'' (2015) and Elsa in the epic fantasy film ''[[King Arthur: Legend of the Sword]]'' (2017).\n\n==Early life==\nMcGrath was raised in [[Ashford, County Wicklow]], Ireland, by Paul, who works with computers, and Mary, who works for an Irish designer. She has two older brothers, Sean, an online media manager, and Rory, who is a post-production producer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/woman/life/katie-mcgrath-superstar-in-waiting-28656761.html|title=Katie McGrath superstar in waiting|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=15 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> She studied the International Baccalaureate at [[St. Andrew's College, Dublin|St. Andrew's College]] before graduating from [[Trinity College, Dublin]] with a degree in history with a focus in Russian history.<ref name=\"TheGloss1\">{{cite journal |first=Anna|last=Carey |url=http://thegloss.ie/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=146&Itemid=1&ed=13 |title=The Sorcerer's Apprentice |work=The Gloss Magazine |date=October 2008 |accessdate=8 December 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218215555/http://thegloss.ie/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=146&Itemid=1&ed=13 |archivedate=18 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMcGrath originally sought to work in fashion journalism and took on a job at [[Image (magazine)|''Image'']] magazine<ref name=\"TheGloss1\" /> before becoming a wardrobe assistant on the set of ''[[The Tudors]]''. While working on ''The Tudors'', McGrath was advised to try acting, so she sent photographs to Irish agents.<ref name=\"SundayHerald\">{{cite news |url=http://sundayheraldsalon.com/salon/2008/10/shes_magic.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408064322/http://sundayheraldsalon.com/salon/2008/10/shes_magic.html |work=Sunday Herald Salon |title=She's magic |url-status=dead|date=4 October 2008 |archivedate=8 April 2009 |accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref> She said:\n{{Quote|Being an actress was kind of like when you're a kid, and you want to run away and join the circus, it's something you really want to do, but then you grew up and got a proper job. It was a dream, but I didn't think it would ever be reality, and yet here I am!<ref name=\"SundayHerald\"/>}}\n\nMcGrath was cast in ''Damage'', an Irish TV-movie in 2007. She also starred in the play ''La Marea'' at the [[Dublin Theatre Festival]] in the same year.<ref>[http://www.bedrockproductions.com/productions/la-marea/ bedrockproductions] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110905063924/http://www.bedrockproductions.com/productions/la-marea/ |date=5 September 2011 }}</ref> She appeared in the feature films ''Eden'' and ''[[Freakdog]]'' in 2008, before being cast as Morgana Pendragon in ''[[Merlin (2008 TV series)|Merlin]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title='Merlin' Katie McGrath final series Q&A|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/merlin/interviews/a442593/merlin-katie-mcgrath-qa-ive-been-privileged-to-be-part-of-this/|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=14 October 2016|date=4 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, McGrath starred in a five-part [[docudrama]] for [[Channel 4]] exploring the life of Queen [[Elizabeth II]], ''[[The Queen (2009 docudrama)|The Queen]]'', in which she played a young [[Princess Margaret]].<ref name=\"Guardian1\">{{cite news |title=Five actresses to play the Queen for C4|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jan/28/channel-4-queen-actresses|accessdate=4 March 2009 |date=27 January 2009}}</ref> [[Emilia Fox]] portrayed Elizabeth II in the same episode in which McGrath appeared; the two had previously worked together as sisters [[Morgause]] and [[Morgan Le Fay|Morgana]] in ''[[Merlin (2008 TV series)|Merlin]]''. In 2010, McGrath was cast in [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s directorial debut [[W.E. (film)|''W.E.'']], an [[Edward VIII]] biopic. McGrath played [[Thelma Furness, Viscountess Furness|Lady Furness]], the king's former mistress who introduces him to [[Wallis Simpson]].<ref name=\"Digital Spy\">{{cite news|title=Katie McGrath praises 'fantastic' Madonna |work=[[Digital Spy]] |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a281030/katie-mcgrath-praises-fantastic-madonna.html |accessdate=8 October 2010 | location=London |date=8 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n2011 saw McGrath film the comedy-drama ''[[A Princess for Christmas]]'' in Romania.<ref name=\"Film New Europe\">{{cite news |author=Blaga, Lulia |title=PRODUCTION: Christmas at Castlebury Hall Will Shoot in Romania |publisher=Film New Europe |url=http://www.filmneweurope.com/news/romania/production-christmas-at-castlebury-hall-will-shoot-in-romania |accessdate=17 May 2011 |date=25 February 2011 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424123348/http://www.filmneweurope.com/news/romania/production-christmas-at-castlebury-hall-will-shoot-in-romania |archivedate=24 April 2011  }}</ref> In September 2011, McGrath voice-acted the characters in the Irish animated short film ''Tr\u00edd an Stoirm'' (''Through the Storm'').<ref>{{cite web|title=Short Film of the Week: Watch Tr\u00edd an Stoirm by Fred Burdy {{!}} Film Ireland|url=http://filmireland.net/2014/01/08/short-film-of-the-week-watch-trid-an-stoirm-by-fred-burdy/|website=filmireland.net|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref> Later that month, McGrath was cast as Oriane Congost in ''[[Labyrinth (TV miniseries)|Labyrinth]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katie McGrath: 'Labyrinth is gritty'|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a356685/katie-mcgrath-ridley-scotts-labyrinth-is-gritty-and-real/|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=14 October 2016|date=20 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nMcGrath was reunited with her ''The Tudors'' co-star and close friend [[Jonathan Rhys Meyers]] in [[NBC]] and [[Sky Living]]'s horror drama TV series ''[[Dracula (2013 TV series)|Dracula]]''; she portrayed [[Lucy Westenra]].<ref name=\"iftn\">{{cite web |url = http://www.iftn.ie/actors/actorsnews/?act1=record&aid=73&rid=4285761&tpl=archnews|title = Victoria Smurfit To Sink Teeth into Jonathan Rhys Meyers' 'Dracula'|date = 4 February 2013|work = [[Irish Film and Television Network|IFTN]]|accessdate = 4 February 2013}}</ref> In June 2013, McGrath co-starred in episode four of the Channel 4 show ''[[Dates (TV series)|Dates]]'' as a young lesbian on the dating scene alongside [[Gemma Chan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=New Channel 4 series \"Dates\" features gorgeous, complex lesbian couple - AfterEllen|url=http://www.afterellen.com/general-news/108235-new-channel-4-series-dates-features-gorgeous-complex-lesbian-couple|website=AfterEllen|accessdate=14 October 2016|date=26 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, McGrath co-starred in a [[Hozier (musician)|Hozier]] music video for the song \"From Eden\".<ref name=\"Irish Independent\">{{cite news|title=Hozier releases new video for 'From Eden' featuring Katie McGrath |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/music-news/hozier-releases-new-video-for-from-eden-featuring-katie-mcgrath-30756852.html | work=[[Irish Independent]] | date=19 November 2014 | accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, McGrath had a supporting role as Zara in the film ''[[Jurassic World]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/judy-greer-joins-jurassic-world-693459|title=Judy Greer Joins ''Jurassic World''|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Borys |last=Kit |date=3 April 2014 |accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref> and starred in the [[Crackle (company)|Crackle]] original spy-thriller, ''[[The Throwaways (film)|The Throwaways]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thevideoink.com/news/crackle-premieres-jeremy-renner-produced-movie-throwaways/#.Vm7nFeKlZT4 |title=Crackle Premieres Jeremy Renner-Produced Movie \u2018The Throwaways\u2019 |work=[[Videoink]] | date=30 January 2015 |accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nMcGrath portrayed the lead role in the first season of Chiller\u2019s original horror series ''[[Slasher (TV series)|Slasher]]'', which premiered on 4 March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title='Slasher' star Katie McGrath's character gets a bloody good welcome|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2016/03/30/slasher-star-katie-mcgraths-character-gets-a-bloody-good-welcome|website=Toronto Sun|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, it was announced that McGrath would play the recurring role of [[Lena Luthor]] in the second season of ''[[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/08/04/supergirl-katie-mcgrath-lena-luthor-cast-season-2-the-cw/|title=''Supergirl'' Lands ''Merlin''{{'s}} Katie McGrath as Lex's Sister Lena Luthor|first=Michael|last=Ausiello|date=4 August 2016|publisher=[[TVLine]]|accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nerdmuch.com/news/35449/supergirl-cast-lena-luthor-katie-mcgrath/ |title=''Supergirl'' Finds Its Lena Luthor in ''Jurassic World''{{'s}} Katie McGrath |first=Elizabeth |last=Bernstein |work=Nerd Much? |date=4 August 2016 |accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref> She debuted in the season two premiere episode titled \"[[The Adventures of Supergirl]]\" and was promoted to a series regular in March 2017 and still maintains this role in season 5.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/supergirl-season-2-spoilers-cw-releases-first-official-photos-katie-mcgrath-lena-2414930 |title=\u2018Supergirl\u2019 Season 2 Spoilers: CW Releases First Official Photos Of Katie McGrath As Lena Luthor |last=Saclao |first=Christian |date=12 September 2016|website=ibtimes.com |publisher=[[IBT Media Inc.]] |accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/supergirl-katie-mcgrath-promoted-series-regular-season-3-lena-luthor-the-cw-1202048294/|title=\u2018Supergirl\u2019: Katie McGrath Promoted To Series Regular For Season 3|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=22 March 2017|work=Deadline|access-date=22 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> She appeared as Elsa in [[Guy Ritchie]]'s fantasy film ''[[King Arthur: Legend of the Sword]]'', which was released in May 2017.<ref name=\"hamiltonhodell.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hamiltonhodell.co.uk/cv/client_katie-mcgrath_id_100349.htm|title=Katie McGrath - Hamilton Hodell - CV|website=hamiltonhodell.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, it was announced that McGrath would star alongside Abbie Cornish and Georgina Haig in [[Seven Network]] series ''[[Secret Bridesmaids' Business]]''. The series will be about how a bride's wedding turns deadly after one of the brisdesmaids invites a stranger into their lives. McGrath will star as Saskia, a bisexual lawyer who is described as an intelligent, loyal woman who is holding a secret.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/abbie-cornish-thriller-series-secret-bridesmaids-business-begins-production-1203207988/|title=Abbie Cornish-Led Thriller Series \u2018Secret Bridesmaids\u2019 Business\u2019 Begins Production (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Yang|first=Rachel|last2=Yang|first2=Rachel|date=8 May 2019|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Film roles\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Pebble''\n| Tara\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[W.E.]]''\n| [[Thelma Furness, Viscountess Furness|Lady Thelma Furness]]\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Tr\u00edd an Stoirm''\n| Alice/Banshee\n| Short film; voice role\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Leading Lady (Film)|Leading Lady]]''\n| Jodi Rutherford\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2015\n| ''[[Jurassic World]]''\n| Zara\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Throwaways (film)|The Throwaways]]''\n| Gloria Miller\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[King Arthur: Legend of the Sword]]''\n| Elsa\n| <ref name=\"hamiltonhodell.co.uk\"/>\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Television roles\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Damage''\n| Rachel\n| Television movie\n|-\n|rowspan=4| 2008\n| ''Eden''\n| Trisha\n| Television movie\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Tudors}}''\n| Bess\n| Episode: \"[[List of The Tudors episodes#ep15|His Majesty's Pleasure]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Freakdog]]''\n| Harriet Chambers\n| Television movie\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Roaring Twenties|nolink=1}}''\n| Vixen\n| Television miniseries\n|-\n| 2008\u20132012\n| ''[[Merlin (2008 TV series)|Merlin]]''\n| [[List of Merlin characters#Morgana Pendragon|Morgana Pendragon]]\n| Main role, 57 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''{{sortname|The|Queen|The Queen (TV serial)}}''\n| [[Princess Margaret]]\n| Episode: \"Margaret\"\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''{{sortname|A|Princess for Christmas}}''\n| Jules Daly\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Labyrinth (TV miniseries)|Labyrinth]]''\n| Oriane Congost\n| Television miniseries\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Dates (TV series)|Dates]]''\n| Kate Foster\n| Episode: \"Erica and Kate\"\n|-\n| 2013\u20132014\n| ''[[Dracula (2013 TV series)|Dracula]]''\n| [[Lucy Westenra]]\n| Main role, 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Slasher (TV series)|Slasher]]''\n| Sarah Bennett\n| Main role (season 1), 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\u2013present\n| ''[[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]]''\n| [[Lena Luthor]]\n| Recurring role (season 2); main role (season 3-); 60 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017\n| ''[[Frontier (2016 TV series)|Frontier]]''\n| Elizabeth Carruthers\n| Recurring role; 7 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[Secret Bridesmaids' Business]]''\n|Saskia de Merindol\n|Main role\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Music videos\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist\n|-\n| 2014\n| \"[[From Eden]]\"\n|[[Hozier (musician)|Hozier]]\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n! Refs\n|-\n| 2009\n| Monte-Carlo TV Festival\n| Outstanding Actress - Drama Series\n| ''[[Merlin (2008 TV series)|Merlin]]''\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|title=Irish Film & Television Network {{!}} IFTN {{!}} Company Directory, Irish film Locations, Actors, Crew, Industry events, Jobs {{!}} The Irish Film & Television Network|url=http://www.iftn.ie/?act1=record&aid=73&rid=4282039&sr=1&only=1&hl=Katie+McGrath&tpl=archnews|website=www.iftn.ie|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011\n| Monte-Carlo TV Festival\n| Outstanding Actress - Drama Series\n| ''Merlin''\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|title=In Full: Monte Carlo TV Festival fiction nominees|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a315649/in-full-monte-carlo-tv-festival-fiction-nominees/|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=2 November 2016|date=20 April 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018\n|[[2018 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n|Choice Scene Stealer\n|''[[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]]''\n| {{nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.moviefone.com/2018/06/22/teen-choice-awards-2018-heres-the-full-list-of-nominations/|title=Teen Choice Awards 2018: Here's the Full List of Nominations|last=|first=|date=|work=Moviefone|access-date=25 June 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|nm2692146|Katie McGrath}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGrath, Katie}}\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from County Wicklow]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Irish film actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish television actresses]]\n[[Category:People educated at St. Andrew's College, Dublin]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish actress}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Katie McGrath\n| image              = Katie McGrath 20100701 Japan Expo 3 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = McGrath at Comic Con France in 2010\n| birth_date         = <!-- Per WP:DOB, do NOT add unless a strong source (i.e. an article) is provided. Unsourced comments from her co-stars DO NOT count. -->\n| birth_place        = [[Ashford, County Wicklow]], Ireland\n| education          = Trinity College, Dublin<ref name=\"TheGloss1\" />\n| occupation         = Actress <!-- DO NOT add model here as McGrath is not known for being a model -->\n| yearsactive        = 2007\u2013present\n| spouse             =\n}}\n\n'''Katie McGrath''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|'|g|r|\u0251:}})<!--Do NOT add her birthday unless a strong source (i.e. an article) is provided. Unsourced comments from her co-stars DO NOT count. --> is an Irish actress.<!-- NOTE: She is primarily known as an actress. \"Model\" is in the infobox.--><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/what-katies-doing-next-k38hrgn77vh|title=What Katie\u2019s doing next|last=|first=|date=|work=thetimes.co.uk|access-date=1 October 2019|language=en}}</ref> In television, she is best known for portraying [[Morgan le Fay|Morgana]] on the [[BBC One]] series [[Merlin (2008 TV series)|''Merlin'']] (2008\u20132012), [[Lucy Westenra]] on the British-American series ''[[Dracula (2013 TV series)|Dracula]]'' (2013\u20132014), Sarah Bennett in the first season of the Canadian horror anthology series ''[[Slasher (TV series)|Slasher]]'' (2016) and for her role as [[Lena Luthor]] on the American superhero series ''[[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]]'' (2016\u2013present). Her film roles include [[Thelma Furness, Viscountess Furness|Lady Thelma Furness]] in the drama film ''[[W.E.]]'' and Jules Daley in the Christmas movie  ''[[A Princess for Christmas]]'', (2011), Zara Young in the science fiction adventure film ''[[Jurassic World]]'' (2015) and Elsa in the epic fantasy film ''[[King Arthur: Legend of the Sword]]'' (2017).\n\n==Early life==\nMcGrath was raised in [[Ashford, County Wicklow]], Ireland, by Paul, who works with computers, and Mary, who works for an Irish designer. She has two older brothers, Sean, an online media manager, and Rory, who is a post-production producer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/woman/life/katie-mcgrath-superstar-in-waiting-28656761.html|title=Katie McGrath superstar in waiting|work=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|access-date=15 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> She studied the International Baccalaureate at [[St. Andrew's College, Dublin|St. Andrew's College]] before graduating from [[Trinity College, Dublin]] with a degree in history with a focus in Russian history.<ref name=\"TheGloss1\">{{cite journal |first=Anna|last=Carey |url=http://thegloss.ie/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=146&Itemid=1&ed=13 |title=The Sorcerer's Apprentice |work=The Gloss Magazine |date=October 2008 |accessdate=8 December 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218215555/http://thegloss.ie/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=146&Itemid=1&ed=13 |archivedate=18 December 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMcGrath originally sought to work in fashion journalism and took on a job at [[Image (magazine)|''Image'']] magazine<ref name=\"TheGloss1\" /> before becoming a wardrobe assistant on the set of ''[[The Tudors]]''. While working on ''The Tudors'', McGrath was advised to try acting, so she sent photographs to Irish agents.<ref name=\"SundayHerald\">{{cite news |url=http://sundayheraldsalon.com/salon/2008/10/shes_magic.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408064322/http://sundayheraldsalon.com/salon/2008/10/shes_magic.html |work=Sunday Herald Salon |title=She's magic |url-status=dead|date=4 October 2008 |archivedate=8 April 2009 |accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref> She said:\n{{Quote|Being an actress was kind of like when you're a kid, and you want to run away and join the circus, it's something you really want to do, but then you grew up and got a proper job. It was a dream, but I didn't think it would ever be reality, and yet here I am!<ref name=\"SundayHerald\"/>}}\n\nMcGrath was cast in ''Damage'', an Irish TV-movie in 2007. She also starred in the play ''La Marea'' at the [[Dublin Theatre Festival]] in the same year.<ref>[http://www.bedrockproductions.com/productions/la-marea/ bedrockproductions] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110905063924/http://www.bedrockproductions.com/productions/la-marea/ |date=5 September 2011 }}</ref> She appeared in the feature films ''Eden'' and ''[[Freakdog]]'' in 2008, before being cast as Morgana Pendragon in ''[[Merlin (2008 TV series)|Merlin]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title='Merlin' Katie McGrath final series Q&A|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/merlin/interviews/a442593/merlin-katie-mcgrath-qa-ive-been-privileged-to-be-part-of-this/|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=14 October 2016|date=4 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, McGrath starred in a five-part [[docudrama]] for [[Channel 4]] exploring the life of Queen [[Elizabeth II]], ''[[The Queen (2009 docudrama)|The Queen]]'', in which she played a young [[Princess Margaret]].<ref name=\"Guardian1\">{{cite news |title=Five actresses to play the Queen for C4|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/jan/28/channel-4-queen-actresses|accessdate=4 March 2009 |date=27 January 2009}}</ref> [[Emilia Fox]] portrayed Elizabeth II in the same episode in which McGrath appeared; the two had previously worked together as sisters [[Morgause]] and [[Morgan Le Fay|Morgana]] in ''[[Merlin (2008 TV series)|Merlin]]''. In 2010, McGrath was cast in [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s directorial debut [[W.E. (film)|''W.E.'']], an [[Edward VIII]] biopic. McGrath played [[Thelma Furness, Viscountess Furness|Lady Furness]], the king's former mistress who introduces him to [[Wallis Simpson]].<ref name=\"Digital Spy\">{{cite news|title=Katie McGrath praises 'fantastic' Madonna |work=[[Digital Spy]] |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a281030/katie-mcgrath-praises-fantastic-madonna.html |accessdate=8 October 2010 | location=London |date=8 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n2011 saw McGrath film the comedy-drama ''[[A Princess for Christmas]]'' in Romania.<ref name=\"Film New Europe\">{{cite news |author=Blaga, Lulia |title=PRODUCTION: Christmas at Castlebury Hall Will Shoot in Romania |publisher=Film New Europe |url=http://www.filmneweurope.com/news/romania/production-christmas-at-castlebury-hall-will-shoot-in-romania |accessdate=17 May 2011 |date=25 February 2011 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424123348/http://www.filmneweurope.com/news/romania/production-christmas-at-castlebury-hall-will-shoot-in-romania |archivedate=24 April 2011  }}</ref> In September 2011, McGrath voice-acted the characters in the Irish animated short film ''Tr\u00edd an Stoirm'' (''Through the Storm'').<ref>{{cite web|title=Short Film of the Week: Watch Tr\u00edd an Stoirm by Fred Burdy {{!}} Film Ireland|url=http://filmireland.net/2014/01/08/short-film-of-the-week-watch-trid-an-stoirm-by-fred-burdy/|website=filmireland.net|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref> Later that month, McGrath was cast as Oriane Congost in ''[[Labyrinth (TV miniseries)|Labyrinth]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katie McGrath: 'Labyrinth is gritty'|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a356685/katie-mcgrath-ridley-scotts-labyrinth-is-gritty-and-real/|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=14 October 2016|date=20 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nMcGrath was reunited with her ''The Tudors'' co-star and close friend [[Jonathan Rhys Meyers]] in [[NBC]] and [[Sky Living]]'s horror drama TV series ''[[Dracula (2013 TV series)|Dracula]]''; she portrayed [[Lucy Westenra]].<ref name=\"iftn\">{{cite web |url = http://www.iftn.ie/actors/actorsnews/?act1=record&aid=73&rid=4285761&tpl=archnews|title = Victoria Smurfit To Sink Teeth into Jonathan Rhys Meyers' 'Dracula'|date = 4 February 2013|work = [[Irish Film and Television Network|IFTN]]|accessdate = 4 February 2013}}</ref> In June 2013, McGrath co-starred in episode four of the Channel 4 show ''[[Dates (TV series)|Dates]]'' as a young lesbian on the dating scene alongside [[Gemma Chan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=New Channel 4 series \"Dates\" features gorgeous, complex lesbian couple - AfterEllen|url=http://www.afterellen.com/general-news/108235-new-channel-4-series-dates-features-gorgeous-complex-lesbian-couple|website=AfterEllen|accessdate=14 October 2016|date=26 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, McGrath co-starred in a [[Hozier (musician)|Hozier]] music video for the song \"From Eden\".<ref name=\"Irish Independent\">{{cite news|title=Hozier releases new video for 'From Eden' featuring Katie McGrath |url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/music-news/hozier-releases-new-video-for-from-eden-featuring-katie-mcgrath-30756852.html | work=[[Irish Independent]] | date=19 November 2014 | accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, McGrath had a supporting role as Zara in the film ''[[Jurassic World]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/judy-greer-joins-jurassic-world-693459|title=Judy Greer Joins ''Jurassic World''|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Borys |last=Kit |date=3 April 2014 |accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref> and starred in the [[Crackle (company)|Crackle]] original spy-thriller, ''[[The Throwaways (film)|The Throwaways]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thevideoink.com/news/crackle-premieres-jeremy-renner-produced-movie-throwaways/#.Vm7nFeKlZT4 |title=Crackle Premieres Jeremy Renner-Produced Movie \u2018The Throwaways\u2019 |work=[[Videoink]] | date=30 January 2015 |accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nMcGrath portrayed the lead role in the first season of Chiller\u2019s original horror series ''[[Slasher (TV series)|Slasher]]'', which premiered on 4 March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title='Slasher' star Katie McGrath's character gets a bloody good welcome|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2016/03/30/slasher-star-katie-mcgraths-character-gets-a-bloody-good-welcome|website=Toronto Sun|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, it was announced that McGrath would play the recurring role of [[Lena Luthor]] in the second season of ''[[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/08/04/supergirl-katie-mcgrath-lena-luthor-cast-season-2-the-cw/|title=''Supergirl'' Lands ''Merlin''{{'s}} Katie McGrath as Lex's Sister Lena Luthor|first=Michael|last=Ausiello|date=4 August 2016|publisher=[[TVLine]]|accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nerdmuch.com/news/35449/supergirl-cast-lena-luthor-katie-mcgrath/ |title=''Supergirl'' Finds Its Lena Luthor in ''Jurassic World''{{'s}} Katie McGrath |first=Elizabeth |last=Bernstein |work=Nerd Much? |date=4 August 2016 |accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref> She debuted in the season two premiere episode titled \"[[The Adventures of Supergirl]]\" and was promoted to a series regular in March 2017 and still maintains this role in season 5.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/supergirl-season-2-spoilers-cw-releases-first-official-photos-katie-mcgrath-lena-2414930 |title=\u2018Supergirl\u2019 Season 2 Spoilers: CW Releases First Official Photos Of Katie McGrath As Lena Luthor |last=Saclao |first=Christian |date=12 September 2016|website=ibtimes.com |publisher=[[IBT Media Inc.]] |accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/supergirl-katie-mcgrath-promoted-series-regular-season-3-lena-luthor-the-cw-1202048294/|title=\u2018Supergirl\u2019: Katie McGrath Promoted To Series Regular For Season 3|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=22 March 2017|work=Deadline|access-date=22 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> She appeared as Elsa in [[Guy Ritchie]]'s fantasy film ''[[King Arthur: Legend of the Sword]]'', which was released in May 2017.<ref name=\"hamiltonhodell.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hamiltonhodell.co.uk/cv/client_katie-mcgrath_id_100349.htm|title=Katie McGrath - Hamilton Hodell - CV|website=hamiltonhodell.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, it was announced that McGrath would star alongside Abbie Cornish and Georgina Haig in [[Seven Network]] series ''[[Secret Bridesmaids' Business]]''. The series will be about how a bride's wedding turns deadly after one of the brisdesmaids invites a stranger into their lives. McGrath will star as Saskia, a bisexual lawyer who is described as an intelligent, loyal woman who is holding a secret.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/abbie-cornish-thriller-series-secret-bridesmaids-business-begins-production-1203207988/|title=Abbie Cornish-Led Thriller Series \u2018Secret Bridesmaids\u2019 Business\u2019 Begins Production (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Yang|first=Rachel|last2=Yang|first2=Rachel|date=8 May 2019|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Film roles\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Pebble''\n| Tara\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[W.E.]]''\n| [[Thelma Furness, Viscountess Furness|Lady Thelma Furness]]\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Tr\u00edd an Stoirm''\n| Alice/Banshee\n| Short film; voice role\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Leading Lady (Film)|Leading Lady]]''\n| Jodi Rutherford\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2015\n| ''[[Jurassic World]]''\n| Zara\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Throwaways (film)|The Throwaways]]''\n| Gloria Miller\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[King Arthur: Legend of the Sword]]''\n| Elsa\n| <ref name=\"hamiltonhodell.co.uk\"/>\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Television roles\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Damage''\n| Rachel\n| Television movie\n|-\n|rowspan=4| 2008\n| ''Eden''\n| Trisha\n| Television movie\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Tudors}}''\n| Bess\n| Episode: \"[[List of The Tudors episodes#ep15|His Majesty's Pleasure]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Freakdog]]''\n| Harriet Chambers\n| Television movie\n|-\n| ''{{sortname|The|Roaring Twenties|nolink=1}}''\n| Vixen\n| Television miniseries\n|-\n| 2008\u20132012\n| ''[[Merlin (2008 TV series)|Merlin]]''\n| [[List of Merlin characters#Morgana Pendragon|Morgana Pendragon]]\n| Main role, 57 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''{{sortname|The|Queen|The Queen (TV serial)}}''\n| [[Princess Margaret]]\n| Episode: \"Margaret\"\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''{{sortname|