{"title_page": "RNAS Yeovilton (HMS Heron)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Redirect|HMS Heron (shore establishment)|ships with the same name|HMS Heron}}{{Infobox military installation\n| name = RNAS Yeovilton\n| ensign=Naval Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg\n| ensign_size=90px\n| location = [[Yeovilton]], [[Somerset]]\n| image = File:Aerial View - RNAS Yeovilton 2006 (2439197008).jpg\n| caption = RNAS Yeovilton Airshow in 2006\n| pushpin_map = Somerset\n| pushpin_label = EGDY\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Somerset\n| coordinates = {{Coord|51|00|31|N|002|38|16|W|region:GB_type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| type = Royal Naval Air Station\n| owner = [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]\n| operator = [[Royal Navy]]\n| current_commander = [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|Commodore]] [[Nick Tindal (Royal Navy officer)|Nick Tindal]]\n| past_commanders = <!-- past notable commander(s) -->\n| elevation = {{Convert|23|m|0}}\n| IATA = YEO\n| ICAO = EGDY\n| r1-number = 04/22\n| r1-length = {{Convert|1463|m|0}}\n| r1-surface = [[Concrete]]\n| r2-number = 09/27\n| r2-length = {{Convert|2310|m|0}}\n| r2-surface = Concrete\n| website = \n}}\n'''Royal Naval Air Station Yeovilton''', or '''RNAS Yeovilton''', {{Airport codes|YEO|EGDY}} ('''HMS ''Heron''''') is an airfield of the [[Royal Navy]] and British Army, sited a few miles north of [[Yeovil]], [[Somerset]]. It is one of two active [[Fleet Air Arm]] bases (the other being [[RNAS Culdrose (HMS Seahawk)|RNAS Culdrose)]] and is currently home to the Royal Navy [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Wildcat HMA2]] and [[Army Air Corps (United Kingdom)|Army Air Corps]] [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Wildcat AH1]] helicopters as well as the Royal Navy's [[Commando Helicopter Force]] [[AgustaWestland AW101|Merlin]] HCi3/3A/4 and [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Wildcat AH1]] helicopters.\n\nThe site consists of {{convert|1000|acre|sqmi km2|1|abbr=on}} of airfield sites plus ranges and minor estates. Royal Naval Air Station (RNAS) Yeovilton is a large multi-role air station with an annual budget of some \u00a361 million. The airfield is also home to the [[Fleet Air Arm Museum]] and the station hosts an annual Air Day in July.\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1938, the potential of the land at Yeovilton for use as an airfield was spotted by [[Westland Aircraft]]'s chief test pilot [[Harald Penrose]] and an offer was made to buy the land. The owners, however{{spaced ndash}}the [[Ecclesiastical Commissioners]] of the [[Church of England]]{{spaced ndash}}refused to sell it. In 1939, the Admiralty Air Division commandeered {{convert|417|acre|ha}} of the land and work began on the construction of the site. The runways being completed in 1941 despite problems with poor drainage. A main runway of {{convert|3645|ft|abbr=on|0}} and three subsidiary runways each of {{convert|3000|ft|abbr=on|0}} had been constructed.<ref name=\"berryman\">{{cite book |title=Somerset airfields in the Second World War |last=Berryman |first=David |year=2006 |publisher=Countryside Books |location=Newbury |isbn=1-85306-864-0 |pages=194\u2013219 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ground Crew Working on Fleet Air Arm Aircraft at Rnas Yeovilton, September 1943 TR1275.jpg|thumb|A Fleet Air Arm Supermarine Seafire being refuelled by a petrol bowser at Yeovilton in September 1943.|alt=A Fleet Air Arm Supermarine Seafire being refuelled by a petrol bowser at Yeovilton in September 1943.|left]]\n[[750 Naval Air Squadron]] was formed at [[RNAS Ford]] on 24 May 1939 from the Royal Navy Observer School, but after Ford was bombed early in the war, it moved to RNAS Yeovilton.<ref name=NN>{{cite web|url=http://www.navynews.co.uk/articles/2002/0202/0002022601.asp|title=50 Years Not Out for 750 Squadron|publisher=[[Navy News]]|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> They were joined by [[751 Naval Air Squadron|751]] and [[752 Naval Air Squadron|752]] Squadrons with the Naval Air Fighter School soon following. In addition Westland Aircraft developed a repair facility at the site.  From July 1940, the site was subjected to [[Luftwaffe]] bombing on several occasions. [[794 Naval Air Squadron]] was the first to be formed at the base and served to train other squadrons to practise aerial gunnery, and part of one of the runways was marked up as a flight deck to practise landing on an aircraft carrier. [[827 Naval Air Squadron]] was also stationed at Yeovilton operating [[Fairey Albacore]]s and later [[Fairey Barracuda|Barracuda]]s starting in May 1943, becoming the first squadron to receive Barracudas in any substantial number.<ref name=\"berryman\"/> Several units which were preparing for embarkation were also stationed at the site during the [[World War II|Second World War]]. Because of pressure on space at the airfield, satellite sites were set up at [[RNAS Charlton Horethorne (HMS Heron II)|Charlton Horethorne]] and [[Henstridge Airfield|Henstridge]] in 1942. A centre for Air Direction Radar was also established at Speckington Manor on the edge of the airfield.<ref name=\"berryman\"/>\n\nAfter the end of the war, Yeovilton became one of the main demobilization centres for the Royal Navy, with many of the men helping to refurbish the runways while they stayed at the base. In 1952, Yeovilton became the shore base for the fleets all-weather fighters. The runways were further extended by [[Taylor Woodrow]] in 1952 and 1957 to cope with jet aircraft. In May 1953, it became the headquarters of Flag Officer Flying Training.<ref name=\"helis\">{{cite web |url=http://www.helis.com/database/?menu=2&tpais=UK&tbase=27&titulo=UK%20RNAS%20Yeovilton |title=RNAS Yeovilton |accessdate=20 February 2008 |work=Helis.com }}</ref>\n\n[[File:899 Shar Yeovilton.jpg|thumb|[[British Aerospace Sea Harrier|BAe Sea Harrier FRS1]] of 899 Naval Air Squadron at Yeovilton Naval Air Station in 1982.]]\nDuring the 1960s, further development work was undertaken, with the School of Fighter Direction returning to the site and the [[De Havilland Venom|Sea Venoms]] being replaced by the [[de Havilland Sea Vixen]]s then in turn by the [[McDonnell-Douglas]] [[F-4 Phantom II|Phantom FG1]] as a carrier-borne fighter. The 1970s saw the Flag Officer, Naval Air Command (FONAC), transferring from [[RNAS Lee-on-Solent (HMS Daedalus)|RNAS Lee-on-Solent]]. Royal Navy fixed wing operations were phased out, and the [[F-4 Phantom II|Phantoms]] transferred to the [[Royal Air Force|RAF]]. The base remained as the home of the Commando Helicopter Squadrons, using the [[Westland Wessex|Wessex]] HU5 and later the [[Westland Sea King|Sea King]] HC4, and the fixed wing [[Fleet Requirements and Aircraft Direction Unit]] (FRADU) and became the main shore base for the Navy's fleet of [[Sea Harrier]] FRS1 (and later, FA2). A ski-jump (now removed) was installed to enable practice of [[STOVL|ski-jump assisted take-offs]].<ref name=\"helis\"/>\n\nIn the mid 1980s Defence Estates announced that many of the Royal Navy ratings married quarters at RNAS Yeovilton were surplus to requirements. As a result, The Welbeck Estate Group acquired in the nearby town of Ilchester two entire estates of apartments in Hermes Place and Lyster Close that were used by personnel at HMS Heron. (Note that while HMS is typically a designation for a ship, the Royal Navy has also used it for land-based [[Stone frigate|establishments]].) These were refurbished and sold to local buyers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yeovilton / HMS Heron|url=http://www.airfieldinformationexchange.org/community/showthread.php?3314-Yeovilton-HMS-Heron/page8|publisher=Airfield Information Exchange|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Projects undertaken since 1969...|url=http://www.welbeckestate.com/site_map.htm|publisher=Wellbeck Estate Group|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nSince 1993 the [[Fleet Air Arm]]'s Memorial Church has been the [[Church of St Bartholomew, Yeovilton|Church of St Bartholomew]] in Yeovilton.<ref name=cloudobservers>{{cite web|title=St Bartholomew\u2019s Church, Yeovilton|url=http://cloudobservers.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2011/10/FAA-Memorial-Church.pdf|publisher=Cloudobservers|accessdate=19 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[800 Naval Air Squadron]], [[801 Naval Air Squadron]] and [[899 Naval Air Squadron]] (training) which operated the [[BAE Sea Harrier|BAE Sea Harrier FA2 and T8]] were disbanded in 2006. The replacement [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II]] will be operated from [[RAF Marham]] and is due to enter service in 2018, when it will equip the [[Queen Elizabeth-class aircraft carrier]]s.\n\nIn July 2006, [[Westland Sea King|Sea King]] HC4 helicopters from RNAS Yeovilton were deployed to Cyprus on [[Operation Highbrow]] to assist with the evacuation of British citizens from Lebanon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/somerset/5191474.stm |title=Helicopters go to aid evacuation  |accessdate=20 February 2008 |work=BBC News  | date=18 July 2006}}</ref> Following the closure of [[RNAS Portland]] (HMS ''Osprey'') in 1999, HMS ''Heron'' became the main shore base for the [[Westland Lynx|Lynx]] fleet.<ref name=\"helis\"/>\n\n=== Commando Helicopter Force \u2013 from Sea King to Merlin ===\n[[File:Royal Navy Sea King Mk 4 Merlin Mk 3 Yeovilton Air Day 2.jpg|alt=A Sea King HC4 (foreground) accompanied by a Merlin HC3 of the Commando Helicopter Force at RNAS Yeovilton.|left|thumb|A Sea King HC4 (foreground) accompanied by a Merlin HC3 of the Commando Helicopter Force at RNAS Yeovilton.]]\nThe [[Strategic Defence and Security Review 2010]] recommended that in order to replace the Navy's ageing [[Westland Sea King#Commando and further developments|Westland Sea King HC4's]] which formed the Commando Helicopter Force at Yeovilton, the RAF's [[AgustaWestland AW101|AgustaWestland AW101 Merlin]] fleet should be transferred to the [[Royal Navy|Royal Navy's]]. To gain experience of operating and maintaining the Merlin, Royal Navy aircrew and engineers were integrated into the Merlin Force at [[RAF Benson]] during 2012.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.forces.net/news/navy/raf-hand-over-merlins-royal-navy|title=RAF Hand Over Merlins to the Royal Navy|date=30 September 2014|work=Forces Network|access-date=14 August 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Merlin fleet was officially handed over to the navy during a ceremony at Benson on 30 September 2014.<ref name=\":02\"/> The ceremony marked the disbandment of the RAF's [[No. 78 Squadron RAF|No. 78 Squadron]] and its replacement at Benson with [[846 Naval Air Squadron]]. During July 2015, [[845 Naval Air Squadron]] reformed at Benson and replaced [[No. 28 Squadron RAF|No. 28 Squadron]] of the RAF which also disbanded.\n\nThe Merlin arrived at Yeovilton when 846 NAS moved from Benson on 26 March 2015. In May of that year, [[848 Naval Air Squadron]] temporarily stood up with the remaining [[Westland Sea King|Sea King HC4]] to cover the last remaining Sea King operations, before the Sea King HC4 was finally retired and the squadron decommissioned on 24 March 2016.<ref name=\"UK Government\">{{cite web|url=http://forces.tv/96268817|title=The Past, Present and Future of the 'Junglie'|date=5 February 2015|website=Forces Network|publisher=Service Sound and Vision Corporation|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2016/march/24/160324-decommissioning-of-sea-king-848-naval-air-squadron|title=It really is goodbye to the 'old girl'|date=24 March 2016|website=Royal Navy|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe last phase of the transition occurred when 845 NAS departed Benson for Yeovilton on 16 June 2016, bringing nearly 15 years of RAF Merlin operations to a close.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2015/march/27/150327-846-home|title=846 NAS comes home to Somerset|date=27 March 2015|website=Royal Navy|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://navynews.co.uk/archive/news/item/15025|title=CHF family reunited as Merlins complete their move from Oxfordshire to Yeovilton|date=17 June 2016|website=Navy News|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Wildcat and Project WINFRA ===\n[[File:Blackcat Formation - RAF Waddington. 05-7-2014 (14580899242).jpg|alt=A Lynx HMA8RSU (top) operated by 815sqn and Wildcat HMA2.|thumb|A Lynx HMA8RSU (top) operated by 815sqn and a Wildcat HMA2.]]\nThe [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat HMA2]] began replacing the [[Westland Lynx|Westland Lynx HMA8]] when the first production aircraft arrived at Yeovilton in January 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://navynews.co.uk/archive/news/item/6905|title=Navy\u2019s first Wildcat makes its debut in Somerset skies|date=28 January 2013|website=Navy News|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> Prior to that, in May 2009, [[700 Naval Air Squadron|700W NAS]] was formed at Yeovilton as the Wildcat Fielding Squadron. The squadron disbanded in July 2014 when it was merged with [[702 Naval Air Squadron|702 NAS]] to form [[825 Naval Air Squadron|825 NAS]], the first operational Wildcat unit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2014/july/31/140731-700w|title=700 (W) Naval Air Squadron bows out on a high|date=31 July 2014|website=Royal Navy|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> The final Wildcat HMA2 for the Royal Navy was delivered to 825 NAS in October 2016, bringing the total number of Royal Navy Wildcats to 28.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2016/october/27/161027-royal-navy-take-delivery-of-their-final-wildcat-helicopter|title=Royal Navy take delivery of their final Wildcat helicopter|date=27 October 2016|website=Royal Navy|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> The Lynx was retired in March 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/royal-navy-lynx-hma8-fleet-bows-out-of-service-435293/|title=Royal Navy Lynx HMA8 fleet bows out of service|date=17 March 2017|work=Flight Global|access-date=18 November 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, the consolidation of the [[Army Air Corps (United Kingdom)|Army Air Corps]] (AAC) for [[Future of the British Army (Army 2020)|Army 2020]] resulted in a large regular aviation regiment of [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Wildcat AH1]] being based at RNAS Yeovilton. As such, all 62 UK military Wildcats on order will operate from Yeovilton.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/360915/desider_77_Oct2014-v1_0.pdf|title=DESider, October 2014, Issue 77|website=www.gov.uk|publisher=Defence Equipment & Support|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref> 1 Regiment has returned from [[RAF G\u00fctersloh|G\u00fctersloh]] in Germany, and merged with 9 Regiment from [[RAF Dishforth|Dishforth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/documents/general/Army2020_Report_v2.pdf|title=Army 2020 Brochure|publisher=British Army|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref> The current [[No. 652 Squadron AAC|652 (Wildcat Fielding) Squadron]] will become 1 Regiment's Wildcat [[Operational Conversion Unit]]. 1 Regiment will form part of the Army Air Corps' Aviation Reconnaissance Force along with [[5 Regiment Army Air Corps|5 Regiment]].\n\nIn order to allow the Army Air Corps to locate their Wildcat helicopters and 750 personnel at Yeovilton, extensive redevelopment of the station began in 2014. Known as Project WINFRA, the work involves eight separate contracts worth a total of \u00a3150 million and is being undertaken by [[Mott MacDonald|Mott McDonald]] and [[Carillion]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insidedio.blog.gov.uk/2017/07/24/all-set-for-takeoff-at-rnas-yeovilton/|title=All Set For Takeoff at RNAS Yeovilton|last=Fife|first=Alastair|date=24 July 2017|website=Inside DIO Blog|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> Building 710, a new three-storey squadron building for 846 Naval Air Squadron was completed in March 2015. The refurbishment of technical facilities and the construction of new quarter master's stores, vehicle garages and facilities, ancillary buildings, a cycle path and car parks was completed and handed to the AAC in November 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insidedio.blog.gov.uk/2015/11/16/work-on-wildcats-new-home-continues-apace/|title=Work on Wildcats' new home continues apace|last=Jeffries|first=Steve|date=16 November 2015|website=Inside DIO Blog|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> Building 661 is the new 1 Regiment headquarters and provides accommodation for 659 Squadron and 661 Squadron.\n\nIn 2016, a new dental centre, a refurbished office building for 825 Naval Air Squadron and a new build squadron building for 815 Naval Air Squadron were completed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insidedio.blog.gov.uk/2016/06/27/wildcat-infrastructure-work-progresses-at-rnas-yeovilton/|title=Wildcat infrastructure work progresses at RNAS Yeovilton|last=Thornton|first=Matt|date=27 June 2016|website=Inside DIO Blog|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> By January 2017, a 500 capacity Senior Rates Mess, Physical and Recreational Training Centre including a gym, Multi Use Games Area and 4G sports pitches and the refurbishment of the medical centre had been completed. Three blocks of Single Living Accommodation which can accommodate 400 personnel were finished in March 2017. In total, the project has provided 508 new single living accommodation bed spaces and 130 service families accommodation bed spaces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insidedio.blog.gov.uk/2017/01/03/dio-delivering-for-the-wildcat-programme/|title=DIO delivering for the Wildcat programme|last=Simmons|first=Emily|date=3 January 2017|website=Inside DIO Blog|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Royal Navy Historic Flight===\n\nThe [[Royal Navy Historic Flight]] was disbanded in March 2019, previously operating at RNAS Yeovilton since 1972.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://navywings.org.uk/royal-navy-historic-flight-stands-down-after-50-years/|title=Royal Navy Historic Flight Stands Down after 50 Years|last=robjones|date=2019-03-29|website=Navy Wings|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Following its disbandment, the remaining aircraft were donated to the Fly Navy Heritage Trust at an approximate value of \u00a31,810,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2020-01-23/HCWS55/|title=Gifting of Royal Navy Historic Flight Aircraft:Written statement - HCWS55|website=UK Parliament|language=English|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> With the aircraft having now been transferred to the civilian register, displays are now funded from charity events run by the Fly Navy Heritage Trust.\n\n==Operations==\nYeovilton is home to the Royal Navy Maritime Wildcat Force (MWF), Royal Navy Commando Helicopter Force (CHF), the Army's Aviation Reconnaissance Force (ARF) and elements of the Royal Navy Fixed Wing Force. The station operates over 100 aircraft and is manned by around 1675 service and 2000 civilian personnel, including [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence (MOD)]] employees and permanent contractors. Training of aircrew and engineers of resident aircraft types is also carried out at RNAS Yeovilton. It is also the location for the RN Fighter Controller School, training surface based aircraft controllers.\n\nThe Commando Helicopter Force has now returned to prioritising its main amphibious role in support of [[Royal Navy]]/[[Royal Marines]] operations after focusing on more than a decade of service in land-locked [[Operation Herrick|Afghanistan]] and prior to that in [[Operation Telic|Iraq]].\n\nDuring periods of busy flying training, pressure on the RNAS Yeovilton circuit is relieved by the use of nearby [[RNAS Merryfield]].\n\n[[727 Naval Air Squadron]] operate the [[Grob G 115|Grob Tutor T1]] in the grading and elementary flying training role.\n\n==Air Day==\nThe station holds an annual air show when the airfield is open to the public. It includes both a flying and static aircraft display. The air day traditionally ends with the [[Commando Helicopter Force]] role demonstration, which sees a mixture of aircraft and land forces demonstrate a land assault delivered from the air.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2018/july/09/180709-yeovilton-air-day|title=A spectacular Air Show at RNAS Yeovilton {{!}} Royal Navy|website=www.royalnavy.mod.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Units==\nFlying and notable non-flying units based at RNAS Yeovilton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/our-organisation/where-we-are/air-stations/rnas-yeovilton|title=RNAS Yeovilton|website=Royal Navy|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/aviation/27829.aspx|title=1 Regiment Army Air Corps|website=The British Army|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/reme/41434.aspx|title=7 Aviation Support Battalion|website=The British Army|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Royal Navy ===\n'''[[Fleet Air Arm]]''' \n* Wildcat Maritime Force\n** [[815 Naval Air Squadron]] \u2013 [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Wildcat HMA2]]\n** [[825 Naval Air Squadron]] \u2013 Wildcat HMA2\n* [[727 Naval Air Squadron]] \u2013 [[Grob G 115|Tutor T1]] \n* Royal Naval Reserve Air Branch\n* Royal Navy School of Fighter Control\n*Royal Navy School of Aircraft Control\n*[[Underwater Escape Training Unit]]\n*[[Black Cats (Royal Navy)|Royal Navy Black Cats]] Display Team\n\n'''[[Joint Helicopter Command]]''' / '''Fleet Air Arm'''\n* [[Commando Helicopter Force]] (Fleet Air Arm / [[Royal Marines]])\n** [[845 Naval Air Squadron]] \u2013 [[AgustaWestland AW101|Commando Merlin HC4/4A]]\n**[[846 Naval Air Squadron]] \u2013 Commando Merlin HC4/HC3i\n**[[847 Naval Air Squadron]] \u2013 Commando Wildcat AH1\n\n=== British Army ===\n'''[[Joint Helicopter Command]]''' '''/ [[Army Air Corps (United Kingdom)|Army Air Corps]]'''\n*Aviation Reconnaissance Force\n**[[1 Regiment Army Air Corps|1 Regiment]]\n***[[No. 652 Squadron AAC|652 Squadron]] \u2013 Wildcat AH1\n***[[No. 659 Squadron AAC|659 Squadron]] \u2013 Wildcat AH1\n***[[No. 661 Squadron AAC|661 Squadron]] \u2013 Wildcat AH1\n'''[[Royal Electrical and Mechanical Engineers]]'''\n* 7 Aviation Support Battalion\n** 73 Aviation Company (Wildcat Support)\n\n==Future==\n===Merlin Life Sustainment Programme (MLSP)===\n\nThe Merlin HC3/3A fleet is currently undergoing an upgrade to HC4 and HC4A to ensure the aircraft are fully capable of deploying in an maritime/amphibious role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://des.mod.uk/merlin-mk4-delivery/|title=https://des.mod.uk/merlin-mk4-delivery/|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The differences between the current HC3 and (former Denmark-bound) HC3A will be almost eliminated in the HC4/4A upgrade (known as the MLSP). This will remove conversion training requirements, as both the HC4 and HC4A variants can be operated under the same training.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.janes.com/images/assets/889/68889/Force_in_transition_The_RN_Commando_Helicopter_Force_MLSP_programme_moves_forward.pdf|title=Janes Guide - MLSP Merlin|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Prior to the upgrade, seven of the airframes have been upgraded to the 'interim HC3' and are serving with 846 NAS. These aircraft will receive the full upgrade after the remaining aircraft have been upgraded to the HC4 and HC4A.<ref name=\"UK Government\" /> The upgraded and ship-optimised Merlin HC4 and HC4A aircraft are being painted in Royal Navy grey, unlike the green 'Junglie' Sea Kings/Merlin HC3\u2019s they replace. Full Operating Capability of the HC4 is expected by December 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.janes.com/images/assets/889/68889/Force_in_transition_The_RN_Commando_Helicopter_Force_MLSP_programme_moves_forward.pdf|title=Janes Guide - MLSP Merlin|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Commanding Officers, Navy==\nIncluded:<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mackie|first1=Colin|title=Royal Navy Appointments from 1865|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Senior%20Royal%20Navy%20Appointments%201865-.pdf|website=gulabin.com|publisher=Colin Mackie, pp. 124\u2013125, December 2017}}</ref>\n* Captain Harry S. Murray-Smith: March 1940 \u2013 May 1942\n* Captain Mervyn S. Thomas: May 1942 \u2013 August 1943\n* Captain E.M. Conolly Abel Smith: August 1943 \u2013 May 1944\n* Captain Charles L. Keighley Peach: May 1944 \u2013 August 1945\n* Captain John B. Heath: August 1945 \u2013 February 1947\n* Captain W. Kaye Edden: February 1947 \u2013 May 1949\n* Captain Walter A. Adair: May 1949 \u2013 January 1951\n* Captain R.T. Paul: January 1951 \u2013 May 1952\n* Captain Eric V. St.G. Morgan: May 1952 \u2013 September 1953\n* Captain Alan F. Black: September 1953 \u2013 July 1955\n* Captain Henry J.F. Lane: July 1955 \u2013 January 1958\n* Captain Desmond B.Law: January 1958 \u2013 January 1960\n* Captain William C. Simpson: January 1960 \u2013 January 1962\n* Captain Rodney H.P. Carver: January 1962 \u2013 February 1964\n* Captain Terence G.V. Percy: February 1964 \u2013 July 1966\n* Captain George C. Baldwin: July 1966 \u2013 May 1968\n* Captain Cyril J. Cunningham: May 1968 \u2013 May 1970\n* Captain Alfred R. Rawbone: May 1970 \u2013 February 1972\n* Captain Keith A. Leppard: February 1972 \u2013 February 1974\n* Captain Joseph J. Phillips: February 1974 \u2013 November 1975\n* Captain Harold J. Abraham: November 1975 \u2013 October 1977\n* Captain Brian J. Williams: October 1977 \u2013 August 1980\n* Captain Michael J.F. Rawlinson: August 1980 \u2013 February 1982\n* Captain Peter J. Williams: February 1982 \u2013 January 1984\n* Captain Robert J. Northard: January 1984 \u2013 February 1986\n* Captain Rodney P. Warwick: February 1986 \u2013 February 1988\n* Captain Colin L. MacGregor: February 1988 \u2013 1989\n* Captain Robin F. Shercliffe: 1989 \u2013 January 1992\n* Captain Ian D. MacKenzie: January 1992 \u2013 August 1993\n* Captain Iain R. Henderson: August 1993 \u2013 1996\n* Commodore Scott Lidbetter: 1996 \u2013 November 1998\n* Commodore Richard J. Clapp: November 1998 \u2013 May 2001\n* Commodore William M. Covington: May 2001 \u2013 July 2003\n* Commodore Alan R.C. Bennett: July 2003 \u2013 November 2005\n* Commodore Christopher L. Palmer: November 2005 \u2013 July 2009\n*Brigadier Mark Noble [[Royal Marines|RM]]: August 2009 \u2013 June 2011<ref>{{cite news|title=RNAS Yeovilton's Commanding Officer meets with council chairman|url=http://www.yeovilexpress.co.uk/news/4709758.print/|publisher=Yeovil Express|date=29 October 2009}}</ref>\n*Commodore Paul Chivers: June 2011 \u2013 November 2012<ref>{{cite news|title=RNAS Yeovilton in Somerset gets new commanding officer|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-13696562|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=8 June 2011}}</ref> \n*Commodore Jock Alexander: December 2012 \u2013 September 2015\n*Commodore Jon Pentreath: September 2015 \u2013 April 2017\n*Commodore Nick Tindal: April 2017 \u2013 current\n\n==See also==\n*[[Westland Aircraft]]\n*[[List of air stations of the Royal Navy]]\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* Mike Verier ''Yeovilton: Defenders of the Fleet'', 1991, Osprey Superbase Series no. 22, 128pp, {{ISBN|1-85532-138-6}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|RNAS Yeovilton}}\n* [http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/The-Fleet/Air-Stations/RNAS-Yeovilton Main Website]\n* {{WAD|EGDY|source=[[DAFIF]]}}\n* {{GCM|EGDY|EGDY / YEO|source=[[DAFIF]]}}\n* {{ASN|YEO}}\n\n<!--Navigation box-->\n\n{{Navy Command (Ministry of Defence)|state=collapsed}}\n{{Royal Navy bases}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:RNAS Yeovilton (HMS ''Heron'')}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeovilton}}\n[[Category:Royal Naval Air Stations in Somerset]]\n[[Category:Airports in England]]\n[[Category:South Somerset]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Redirect|HMS Heron (shore establishment)|ships with the same name|HMS Heron}}{{Infobox military installation\n| name = RNAS Yeovilton\n| ensign=Naval Ensign of the United Kingdom.svg\n| ensign_size=90px\n| location = [[Yeovilton]], [[Somerset]]\n| image = File:Aerial View - RNAS Yeovilton 2006 (2439197008).jpg\n| caption = RNAS Yeovilton Airshow in 2006\n| pushpin_map = Somerset\n| pushpin_label = EGDY\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Somerset\n| coordinates = {{Coord|51|00|31|N|002|38|16|W|region:GB_type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| type = Royal Naval Air Station\n| owner = [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]\n| operator = [[Royal Navy]]\n| current_commander = [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|Commodore]] [[Nick Tindal (Royal Navy officer)|Nick Tindal]]\n| past_commanders = <!-- past notable commander(s) -->\n| elevation = {{Convert|23|m|0}}\n| IATA = YEO\n| ICAO = EGDY\n| r1-number = 04/22\n| r1-length = {{Convert|1463|m|0}}\n| r1-surface = [[Concrete]]\n| r2-number = 09/27\n| r2-length = {{Convert|2310|m|0}}\n| r2-surface = Concrete\n| website = \n}}\n'''Royal Naval Air Station Yeovilton''', or '''RNAS Yeovilton''', {{Airport codes|YEO|EGDY}} ('''HMS ''Heron''''') is an airfield of the [[Royal Navy]] and British Army, sited a few miles north of [[Yeovil]], [[Somerset]]. It is one of two active [[Fleet Air Arm]] bases (the other being [[RNAS Culdrose (HMS Seahawk)|RNAS Culdrose)]] and is currently home to the Royal Navy [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Wildcat HMA2]] and [[Army Air Corps (United Kingdom)|Army Air Corps]] [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Wildcat AH1]] helicopters as well as the Royal Navy's [[Commando Helicopter Force]] [[AgustaWestland AW101|Merlin]] HCi3/3A/4 and [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Wildcat AH1]] helicopters.\n\nThe site consists of {{convert|1000|acre|sqmi km2|1|abbr=on}} of airfield sites plus ranges and minor estates. Royal Naval Air Station (RNAS) Yeovilton is a large multi-role air station with an annual budget of some \u00a361 million. The airfield is also home to the [[Fleet Air Arm Museum]] and the station hosts an annual Air Day in July.\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1938, the potential of the land at Yeovilton for use as an airfield was spotted by [[Westland Aircraft]]'s chief test pilot [[Harald Penrose]] and an offer was made to buy the land. The owners, however{{spaced ndash}}the [[Ecclesiastical Commissioners]] of the [[Church of England]]{{spaced ndash}}refused to sell it. In 1939, the Admiralty Air Division commandeered {{convert|417|acre|ha}} of the land and work began on the construction of the site. The runways being completed in 1941 despite problems with poor drainage. A main runway of {{convert|3645|ft|abbr=on|0}} and three subsidiary runways each of {{convert|3000|ft|abbr=on|0}} had been constructed.<ref name=\"berryman\">{{cite book |title=Somerset airfields in the Second World War |last=Berryman |first=David |year=2006 |publisher=Countryside Books |location=Newbury |isbn=1-85306-864-0 |pages=194\u2013219 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ground Crew Working on Fleet Air Arm Aircraft at Rnas Yeovilton, September 1943 TR1275.jpg|thumb|A Fleet Air Arm Supermarine Seafire being refuelled by a petrol bowser at Yeovilton in September 1943.|alt=A Fleet Air Arm Supermarine Seafire being refuelled by a petrol bowser at Yeovilton in September 1943.|left]]\n[[750 Naval Air Squadron]] was formed at [[RNAS Ford]] on 24 May 1939 from the Royal Navy Observer School, but after Ford was bombed early in the war, it moved to RNAS Yeovilton.<ref name=NN>{{cite web|url=http://www.navynews.co.uk/articles/2002/0202/0002022601.asp|title=50 Years Not Out for 750 Squadron|publisher=[[Navy News]]|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> They were joined by [[751 Naval Air Squadron|751]] and [[752 Naval Air Squadron|752]] Squadrons with the Naval Air Fighter School soon following. In addition Westland Aircraft developed a repair facility at the site.  From July 1940, the site was subjected to [[Luftwaffe]] bombing on several occasions. [[794 Naval Air Squadron]] was the first to be formed at the base and served to train other squadrons to practise aerial gunnery, and part of one of the runways was marked up as a flight deck to practise landing on an aircraft carrier. [[827 Naval Air Squadron]] was also stationed at Yeovilton operating [[Fairey Albacore]]s and later [[Fairey Barracuda|Barracuda]]s starting in May 1943, becoming the first squadron to receive Barracudas in any substantial number.<ref name=\"berryman\"/> Several units which were preparing for embarkation were also stationed at the site during the [[World War II|Second World War]]. Because of pressure on space at the airfield, satellite sites were set up at [[RNAS Charlton Horethorne (HMS Heron II)|Charlton Horethorne]] and [[Henstridge Airfield|Henstridge]] in 1942. A centre for Air Direction Radar was also established at Speckington Manor on the edge of the airfield.<ref name=\"berryman\"/>\n\nAfter the end of the war, Yeovilton became one of the main demobilization centres for the Royal Navy, with many of the men helping to refurbish the runways while they stayed at the base. In 1952, Yeovilton became the shore base for the fleets all-weather fighters. The runways were further extended by [[Taylor Woodrow]] in 1952 and 1957 to cope with jet aircraft. In May 1953, it became the headquarters of Flag Officer Flying Training.<ref name=\"helis\">{{cite web |url=http://www.helis.com/database/?menu=2&tpais=UK&tbase=27&titulo=UK%20RNAS%20Yeovilton |title=RNAS Yeovilton |accessdate=20 February 2008 |work=Helis.com }}</ref>\n\n[[File:899 Shar Yeovilton.jpg|thumb|[[British Aerospace Sea Harrier|BAe Sea Harrier FRS1]] of 899 Naval Air Squadron at Yeovilton Naval Air Station in 1982.]]\nDuring the 1960s, further development work was undertaken, with the School of Fighter Direction returning to the site and the [[De Havilland Venom|Sea Venoms]] being replaced by the [[de Havilland Sea Vixen]]s then in turn by the [[McDonnell-Douglas]] [[F-4 Phantom II|Phantom FG1]] as a carrier-borne fighter. The 1970s saw the Flag Officer, Naval Air Command (FONAC), transferring from [[RNAS Lee-on-Solent (HMS Daedalus)|RNAS Lee-on-Solent]]. Royal Navy fixed wing operations were phased out, and the [[F-4 Phantom II|Phantoms]] transferred to the [[Royal Air Force|RAF]]. The base remained as the home of the Commando Helicopter Squadrons, using the [[Westland Wessex|Wessex]] HU5 and later the [[Westland Sea King|Sea King]] HC4, and the fixed wing [[Fleet Requirements and Aircraft Direction Unit]] (FRADU) and became the main shore base for the Navy's fleet of [[Sea Harrier]] FRS1 (and later, FA2). A ski-jump (now removed) was installed to enable practice of [[STOVL|ski-jump assisted take-offs]].<ref name=\"helis\"/>\n\nIn the mid 1980s Defence Estates announced that many of the Royal Navy ratings married quarters at RNAS Yeovilton were surplus to requirements. As a result, The Welbeck Estate Group acquired in the nearby town of Ilchester two entire estates of apartments in Hermes Place and Lyster Close that were used by personnel at HMS Heron. (Note that while HMS is typically a designation for a ship, the Royal Navy has also used it for land-based [[Stone frigate|establishments]].) These were refurbished and sold to local buyers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yeovilton / HMS Heron|url=http://www.airfieldinformationexchange.org/community/showthread.php?3314-Yeovilton-HMS-Heron/page8|publisher=Airfield Information Exchange|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Projects undertaken since 1969...|url=http://www.welbeckestate.com/site_map.htm|publisher=Wellbeck Estate Group|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nSince 1993 the [[Fleet Air Arm]]'s Memorial Church has been the [[Church of St Bartholomew, Yeovilton|Church of St Bartholomew]] in Yeovilton.<ref name=cloudobservers>{{cite web|title=St Bartholomew\u2019s Church, Yeovilton|url=http://cloudobservers.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2011/10/FAA-Memorial-Church.pdf|publisher=Cloudobservers|accessdate=19 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[800 Naval Air Squadron]], [[801 Naval Air Squadron]] and [[899 Naval Air Squadron]] (training) which operated the [[BAE Sea Harrier|BAE Sea Harrier FA2 and T8]] were disbanded in 2006. The replacement [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II]] will be operated from [[RAF Marham]] and is due to enter service in 2018, when it will equip the [[Queen Elizabeth-class aircraft carrier]]s.\n\nIn July 2006, [[Westland Sea King|Sea King]] HC4 helicopters from RNAS Yeovilton were deployed to Cyprus on [[Operation Highbrow]] to assist with the evacuation of British citizens from Lebanon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/somerset/5191474.stm |title=Helicopters go to aid evacuation  |accessdate=20 February 2008 |work=BBC News  | date=18 July 2006}}</ref> Following the closure of [[RNAS Portland]] (HMS ''Osprey'') in 1999, HMS ''Heron'' became the main shore base for the [[Westland Lynx|Lynx]] fleet.<ref name=\"helis\"/>\n\n=== Commando Helicopter Force \u2013 from Sea King to Merlin ===\n[[File:Royal Navy Sea King Mk 4 Merlin Mk 3 Yeovilton Air Day 2.jpg|alt=A Sea King HC4 (foreground) accompanied by a Merlin HC3 of the Commando Helicopter Force at RNAS Yeovilton.|left|thumb|A Sea King HC4 (foreground) accompanied by a Merlin HC3 of the Commando Helicopter Force at RNAS Yeovilton.]]\nThe [[Strategic Defence and Security Review 2010]] recommended that in order to replace the Navy's ageing [[Westland Sea King#Commando and further developments|Westland Sea King HC4's]] which formed the Commando Helicopter Force at Yeovilton, the RAF's [[AgustaWestland AW101|AgustaWestland AW101 Merlin]] fleet should be transferred to the [[Royal Navy|Royal Navy's]]. To gain experience of operating and maintaining the Merlin, Royal Navy aircrew and engineers were integrated into the Merlin Force at [[RAF Benson]] during 2012.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.forces.net/news/navy/raf-hand-over-merlins-royal-navy|title=RAF Hand Over Merlins to the Royal Navy|date=30 September 2014|work=Forces Network|access-date=14 August 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Merlin fleet was officially handed over to the navy during a ceremony at Benson on 30 September 2014.<ref name=\":02\"/> The ceremony marked the disbandment of the RAF's [[No. 78 Squadron RAF|No. 78 Squadron]] and its replacement at Benson with [[846 Naval Air Squadron]]. During July 2015, [[845 Naval Air Squadron]] reformed at Benson and replaced [[No. 28 Squadron RAF|No. 28 Squadron]] of the RAF which also disbanded.\n\nThe Merlin arrived at Yeovilton when 846 NAS moved from Benson on 26 March 2015. In May of that year, [[848 Naval Air Squadron]] temporarily stood up with the remaining [[Westland Sea King|Sea King HC4]] to cover the last remaining Sea King operations, before the Sea King HC4 was finally retired and the squadron decommissioned on 24 March 2016.<ref name=\"UK Government\">{{cite web|url=http://forces.tv/96268817|title=The Past, Present and Future of the 'Junglie'|date=5 February 2015|website=Forces Network|publisher=Service Sound and Vision Corporation|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2016/march/24/160324-decommissioning-of-sea-king-848-naval-air-squadron|title=It really is goodbye to the 'old girl'|date=24 March 2016|website=Royal Navy|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe last phase of the transition occurred when 845 NAS departed Benson for Yeovilton on 16 June 2016, bringing nearly 15 years of RAF Merlin operations to a close.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2015/march/27/150327-846-home|title=846 NAS comes home to Somerset|date=27 March 2015|website=Royal Navy|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://navynews.co.uk/archive/news/item/15025|title=CHF family reunited as Merlins complete their move from Oxfordshire to Yeovilton|date=17 June 2016|website=Navy News|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Wildcat and Project WINFRA ===\n[[File:Blackcat Formation - RAF Waddington. 05-7-2014 (14580899242).jpg|alt=A Lynx HMA8RSU (top) operated by 815sqn and Wildcat HMA2.|thumb|A Lynx HMA8RSU (top) operated by 815sqn and a Wildcat HMA2.]]\nThe [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat HMA2]] began replacing the [[Westland Lynx|Westland Lynx HMA8]] when the first production aircraft arrived at Yeovilton in January 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://navynews.co.uk/archive/news/item/6905|title=Navy\u2019s first Wildcat makes its debut in Somerset skies|date=28 January 2013|website=Navy News|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> Prior to that, in May 2009, [[700 Naval Air Squadron|700W NAS]] was formed at Yeovilton as the Wildcat Fielding Squadron. The squadron disbanded in July 2014 when it was merged with [[702 Naval Air Squadron|702 NAS]] to form [[825 Naval Air Squadron|825 NAS]], the first operational Wildcat unit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2014/july/31/140731-700w|title=700 (W) Naval Air Squadron bows out on a high|date=31 July 2014|website=Royal Navy|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> The final Wildcat HMA2 for the Royal Navy was delivered to 825 NAS in October 2016, bringing the total number of Royal Navy Wildcats to 28.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2016/october/27/161027-royal-navy-take-delivery-of-their-final-wildcat-helicopter|title=Royal Navy take delivery of their final Wildcat helicopter|date=27 October 2016|website=Royal Navy|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> The Lynx was retired in March 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/royal-navy-lynx-hma8-fleet-bows-out-of-service-435293/|title=Royal Navy Lynx HMA8 fleet bows out of service|date=17 March 2017|work=Flight Global|access-date=18 November 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, the consolidation of the [[Army Air Corps (United Kingdom)|Army Air Corps]] (AAC) for [[Future of the British Army (Army 2020)|Army 2020]] resulted in a large regular aviation regiment of [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Wildcat AH1]] being based at RNAS Yeovilton. As such, all 62 UK military Wildcats on order will operate from Yeovilton.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/360915/desider_77_Oct2014-v1_0.pdf|title=DESider, October 2014, Issue 77|website=www.gov.uk|publisher=Defence Equipment & Support|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref> 1 Regiment has returned from [[RAF G\u00fctersloh|G\u00fctersloh]] in Germany, and merged with 9 Regiment from [[RAF Dishforth|Dishforth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/documents/general/Army2020_Report_v2.pdf|title=Army 2020 Brochure|publisher=British Army|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref> The current [[No. 652 Squadron AAC|652 (Wildcat Fielding) Squadron]] will become 1 Regiment's Wildcat [[Operational Conversion Unit]]. 1 Regiment will form part of the Army Air Corps' Aviation Reconnaissance Force along with [[5 Regiment Army Air Corps|5 Regiment]].\n\nIn order to allow the Army Air Corps to locate their Wildcat helicopters and 750 personnel at Yeovilton, extensive redevelopment of the station began in 2014. Known as Project WINFRA, the work involves eight separate contracts worth a total of \u00a3150 million and is being undertaken by [[Mott MacDonald|Mott McDonald]] and [[Carillion]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insidedio.blog.gov.uk/2017/07/24/all-set-for-takeoff-at-rnas-yeovilton/|title=All Set For Takeoff at RNAS Yeovilton|last=Fife|first=Alastair|date=24 July 2017|website=Inside DIO Blog|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> Building 710, a new three-storey squadron building for 846 Naval Air Squadron was completed in March 2015. The refurbishment of technical facilities and the construction of new quarter master's stores, vehicle garages and facilities, ancillary buildings, a cycle path and car parks was completed and handed to the AAC in November 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insidedio.blog.gov.uk/2015/11/16/work-on-wildcats-new-home-continues-apace/|title=Work on Wildcats' new home continues apace|last=Jeffries|first=Steve|date=16 November 2015|website=Inside DIO Blog|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> Building 661 is the new 1 Regiment headquarters and provides accommodation for 659 Squadron and 661 Squadron.\n\nIn 2016, a new dental centre, a refurbished office building for 825 Naval Air Squadron and a new build squadron building for 815 Naval Air Squadron were completed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insidedio.blog.gov.uk/2016/06/27/wildcat-infrastructure-work-progresses-at-rnas-yeovilton/|title=Wildcat infrastructure work progresses at RNAS Yeovilton|last=Thornton|first=Matt|date=27 June 2016|website=Inside DIO Blog|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> By January 2017, a 500 capacity Senior Rates Mess, Physical and Recreational Training Centre including a gym, Multi Use Games Area and 4G sports pitches and the refurbishment of the medical centre had been completed. Three blocks of Single Living Accommodation which can accommodate 400 personnel were finished in March 2017. In total, the project has provided 508 new single living accommodation bed spaces and 130 service families accommodation bed spaces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insidedio.blog.gov.uk/2017/01/03/dio-delivering-for-the-wildcat-programme/|title=DIO delivering for the Wildcat programme|last=Simmons|first=Emily|date=3 January 2017|website=Inside DIO Blog|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Royal Navy Historic Flight===\n\nThe [[Royal Navy Historic Flight]] was disbanded in March 2019, previously operating at RNAS Yeovilton since 1972.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://navywings.org.uk/royal-navy-historic-flight-stands-down-after-50-years/|title=Royal Navy Historic Flight Stands Down after 50 Years|last=robjones|date=2019-03-29|website=Navy Wings|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Following its disbandment, the remaining aircraft were donated to the Fly Navy Heritage Trust at an approximate value of \u00a31,810,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2020-01-23/HCWS55/|title=Gifting of Royal Navy Historic Flight Aircraft:Written statement - HCWS55|website=UK Parliament|language=English|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> With the aircraft having now been transferred to the civilian register, displays are now funded from charity events run by the Fly Navy Heritage Trust.\n\n==Operations==\nYeovilton is home to the Royal Navy Maritime Wildcat Force (MWF), Royal Navy Commando Helicopter Force (CHF), the Army's Aviation Reconnaissance Force (ARF) and elements of the Royal Navy Fixed Wing Force. The station operates over 100 aircraft and is manned by around 1675 service and 2000 civilian personnel, including [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence (MOD)]] employees and permanent contractors. Training of aircrew and engineers of resident aircraft types is also carried out at RNAS Yeovilton. It is also the location for the RN Fighter Controller School, training surface based aircraft controllers.\n\nThe Commando Helicopter Force has now returned to prioritising its main amphibious role in support of [[Royal Navy]]/[[Royal Marines]] operations after focusing on more than a decade of service in land-locked [[Operation Herrick|Afghanistan]] and prior to that in [[Operation Telic|Iraq]].\n\nDuring periods of busy flying training, pressure on the RNAS Yeovilton circuit is relieved by the use of nearby [[RNAS Merryfield]].\n\n[[727 Naval Air Squadron]] operate the [[Grob G 115|Grob Tutor T1]] in the grading and elementary flying training role.\n\n==Air Day==\nThe station holds an annual air show when the airfield is open to the public. It includes both a flying and static aircraft display. The air day traditionally ends with the [[Commando Helicopter Force]] role demonstration, which sees a mixture of aircraft and land forces demonstrate a land assault delivered from the air.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2018/july/09/180709-yeovilton-air-day|title=A spectacular Air Show at RNAS Yeovilton {{!}} Royal Navy|website=www.royalnavy.mod.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Units==\nFlying and notable non-flying units based at RNAS Yeovilton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/our-organisation/where-we-are/air-stations/rnas-yeovilton|title=RNAS Yeovilton|website=Royal Navy|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/aviation/27829.aspx|title=1 Regiment Army Air Corps|website=The British Army|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.army.mod.uk/reme/41434.aspx|title=7 Aviation Support Battalion|website=The British Army|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Royal Navy ===\n'''[[Fleet Air Arm]]''' \n* Wildcat Maritime Force\n** [[815 Naval Air Squadron]] \u2013 [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Wildcat HMA2]]\n** [[825 Naval Air Squadron]] \u2013 Wildcat HMA2\n* [[727 Naval Air Squadron]] \u2013 [[Grob G 115|Tutor T1]] \n* Royal Naval Reserve Air Branch\n* Royal Navy School of Fighter Control\n*Royal Navy School of Aircraft Control\n*[[Underwater Escape Training Unit]]\n*[[Black Cats (Royal Navy)|Royal Navy Black Cats]] Display Team\n\n'''[[Joint Helicopter Command]]''' / '''Fleet Air Arm'''\n* [[Commando Helicopter Force]] (Fleet Air Arm / [[Royal Marines]])\n** [[845 Naval Air Squadron]] \u2013 [[AgustaWestland AW101|Commando Merlin HC4/4A]]\n**[[846 Naval Air Squadron]] \u2013 Commando Merlin HC4/HC3i\n**[[847 Naval Air Squadron]] \u2013 Commando Wildcat AH1\n\n=== British Army ===\n'''[[Joint Helicopter Command]]''' '''/ [[Army Air Corps (United Kingdom)|Army Air Corps]]'''\n*Aviation Reconnaissance Force\n**[[1 Regiment Army Air Corps|1 Regiment]]\n***[[No. 652 Squadron AAC|652 Squadron]] \u2013 Wildcat AH1\n***[[No. 659 Squadron AAC|659 Squadron]] \u2013 Wildcat AH1\n***[[No. 661 Squadron AAC|661 Squadron]] \u2013 Wildcat AH1\n'''[[Royal Electrical and Mechanical Engineers]]'''\n* 7 Aviation Support Battalion\n** 73 Aviation Company (Wildcat Support)\n\n==Future==\n===Merlin Life Sustainment Programme (MLSP)===\n\nThe Merlin HC3/3A fleet is currently undergoing an upgrade to HC4 and HC4A to ensure the aircraft are fully capable of deploying in an maritime/amphibious role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://des.mod.uk/merlin-mk4-delivery/|title=https://des.mod.uk/merlin-mk4-delivery/|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The differences between the current HC3 and (former Denmark-bound) HC3A will be almost eliminated in the HC4/4A upgrade (known as the MLSP). This will remove conversion training requirements, as both the HC4 and HC4A variants can be operated under the same training.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.janes.com/images/assets/889/68889/Force_in_transition_The_RN_Commando_Helicopter_Force_MLSP_programme_moves_forward.pdf|title=Janes Guide - MLSP Merlin|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Prior to the upgrade, seven of the airframes have been upgraded to the 'interim HC3' and are serving with 846 NAS. These aircraft will receive the full upgrade after the remaining aircraft have been upgraded to the HC4 and HC4A.<ref name=\"UK Government\" /> The upgraded and ship-optimised Merlin HC4 and HC4A aircraft are being painted in Royal Navy grey, unlike the green 'Junglie' Sea Kings/HC3\u2019s they replace. Full Operating Capability of the HC4 is expected by December 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.janes.com/images/assets/889/68889/Force_in_transition_The_RN_Commando_Helicopter_Force_MLSP_programme_moves_forward.pdf|title=Janes Guide - MLSP Merlin|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Commanding Officers, Navy==\nIncluded:<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mackie|first1=Colin|title=Royal Navy Appointments from 1865|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Senior%20Royal%20Navy%20Appointments%201865-.pdf|website=gulabin.com|publisher=Colin Mackie, pp. 124\u2013125, December 2017}}</ref>\n* Captain Harry S. Murray-Smith: March 1940 \u2013 May 1942\n* Captain Mervyn S. Thomas: May 1942 \u2013 August 1943\n* Captain E.M. Conolly Abel Smith: August 1943 \u2013 May 1944\n* Captain Charles L. Keighley Peach: May 1944 \u2013 August 1945\n* Captain John B. Heath: August 1945 \u2013 February 1947\n* Captain W. Kaye Edden: February 1947 \u2013 May 1949\n* Captain Walter A. Adair: May 1949 \u2013 January 1951\n* Captain R.T. Paul: January 1951 \u2013 May 1952\n* Captain Eric V. St.G. Morgan: May 1952 \u2013 September 1953\n* Captain Alan F. Black: September 1953 \u2013 July 1955\n* Captain Henry J.F. Lane: July 1955 \u2013 January 1958\n* Captain Desmond B.Law: January 1958 \u2013 January 1960\n* Captain William C. Simpson: January 1960 \u2013 January 1962\n* Captain Rodney H.P. Carver: January 1962 \u2013 February 1964\n* Captain Terence G.V. Percy: February 1964 \u2013 July 1966\n* Captain George C. Baldwin: July 1966 \u2013 May 1968\n* Captain Cyril J. Cunningham: May 1968 \u2013 May 1970\n* Captain Alfred R. Rawbone: May 1970 \u2013 February 1972\n* Captain Keith A. Leppard: February 1972 \u2013 February 1974\n* Captain Joseph J. Phillips: February 1974 \u2013 November 1975\n* Captain Harold J. Abraham: November 1975 \u2013 October 1977\n* Captain Brian J. Williams: October 1977 \u2013 August 1980\n* Captain Michael J.F. Rawlinson: August 1980 \u2013 February 1982\n* Captain Peter J. Williams: February 1982 \u2013 January 1984\n* Captain Robert J. Northard: January 1984 \u2013 February 1986\n* Captain Rodney P. Warwick: February 1986 \u2013 February 1988\n* Captain Colin L. MacGregor: February 1988 \u2013 1989\n* Captain Robin F. Shercliffe: 1989 \u2013 January 1992\n* Captain Ian D. MacKenzie: January 1992 \u2013 August 1993\n* Captain Iain R. Henderson: August 1993 \u2013 1996\n* Commodore Scott Lidbetter: 1996 \u2013 November 1998\n* Commodore Richard J. Clapp: November 1998 \u2013 May 2001\n* Commodore William M. Covington: May 2001 \u2013 July 2003\n* Commodore Alan R.C. Bennett: July 2003 \u2013 November 2005\n* Commodore Christopher L. Palmer: November 2005 \u2013 July 2009\n*Brigadier Mark Noble [[Royal Marines|RM]]: August 2009 \u2013 June 2011<ref>{{cite news|title=RNAS Yeovilton's Commanding Officer meets with council chairman|url=http://www.yeovilexpress.co.uk/news/4709758.print/|publisher=Yeovil Express|date=29 October 2009}}</ref>\n*Commodore Paul Chivers: June 2011 \u2013 November 2012<ref>{{cite news|title=RNAS Yeovilton in Somerset gets new commanding officer|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-13696562|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=8 June 2011}}</ref> \n*Commodore Jock Alexander: December 2012 \u2013 September 2015\n*Commodore Jon Pentreath: September 2015 \u2013 April 2017\n*Commodore Nick Tindal: April 2017 \u2013 current\n\n==See also==\n*[[Westland Aircraft]]\n*[[List of air stations of the Royal Navy]]\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* Mike Verier ''Yeovilton: Defenders of the Fleet'', 1991, Osprey Superbase Series no. 22, 128pp, {{ISBN|1-85532-138-6}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|RNAS Yeovilton}}\n* [http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/The-Fleet/Air-Stations/RNAS-Yeovilton Main Website]\n* {{WAD|EGDY|source=[[DAFIF]]}}\n* {{GCM|EGDY|EGDY / YEO|source=[[DAFIF]]}}\n* {{ASN|YEO}}\n\n<!--Navigation box-->\n\n{{Navy Command (Ministry of Defence)|state=collapsed}}\n{{Royal Navy bases}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:RNAS Yeovilton (HMS ''Heron'')}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeovilton}}\n[[Category:Royal Naval Air Stations in Somerset]]\n[[Category:Airports in England]]\n[[Category:South Somerset]]\n", "name_user": "The Beanster", "label": "safe", "comment": "Addition of \u201cMerlin\u201d for clarification", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RNAS_Yeovilton_(HMS_Heron)"}
